{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "We suspect this was partly because of the customization template we provided in ChatLab, which explicitly nudged participants to enter information about themselves and the chatbot, making them think about not just who the chatbot should be but also who they were.",
    "On the one hand, aside from a few participants (P1, P3, P5) who consistently interacted with the same persona (with incremental changes), the majority of participants created and engaged with multiple personas.",
    "At times, they asked the same questions from multiple personas; other times, they sought support for various struggles from each persona.",
    "Specifically, aligning with yet extending beyond conventional supportive and compassionate personas such as mental health professionals and close friends [16,59], participants customized the chatbots to act as those who had caused pain or stress to them (e.g., irritable advisor, ex-partner).",
    "As such, they were able to confront their inner struggles and vent their unresolved anger and regret."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Specifically, aligning with yet extending beyond conventional supportive and compassionate personas such as mental health professionals and close friends [16,59], participants customized the chatbots to act as those who had caused pain or stress to them (e.g., irritable advisor, ex-partner)."
